    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(center)"><placeName>Senecaville O.</placeName>
                <date>June 20. 1867</date>.</p>
            <p><addressee>Mr. Leeser</addressee>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir,</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">As I have the impression that<lb/> you never read the “Israelite” I
                take the liberty<lb/> to send you the <sic>inclosed</sic> article cut from the<lb/>
                Israelite. I thought it would be interesting to<lb/> you to learn that thoughts so
                favorable to the<lb/> reality of miracles appear in that paper. I take<lb/> it for
                granted that this article is much more<lb/> agreeable to your views than the
                treatment which<lb/> the same subject and the manna receive in<lb/>
                <persName>Dr. Wise's</persName> History.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">In contending, however, for the historical<lb/> truth of miracles. I
                am afraid that among<lb/> your people we have now a mighty current<lb/> against us.
                When I was in <placeName>Cincinnati</placeName> more<lb/> than a year ago, examining
                the <persName>Licking Co.</persName> relics,<lb/> I met a <persName>Mr.
                    Moering</persName>, an aged Israelite, who told<lb/> me that he believed that
                the whole Jewish commu=<lb/>nity were sliding into the views of <persName>Drs
                    Lilienthal</persName><lb/> and <persName>Wise</persName> on miracles, and that
                these men<lb/> would succeed in what they had undertaken<lb/> so that in twenty
                years orthodox Judaism would<lb/> be lost. And what appeared to me stranger<lb/> he
                himself appeared to look on it as all right.<lb/> He intimated that there might have
                been some con=<lb/>cealed knowledge and use of gunpowder by
                    <persName>Moses</persName><lb/> in the destruction of the company of
                    <persName>Korah</persName>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">The common way of speaking of such things<lb/> among Gentiles is
                just this, that the Jews are now<lb/> going right into infidelity, and that they are
                proving<lb/> unfaithful to their great trust in the preservation<lb/> of the
                truth.</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>Do not understand me however<lb/> as writing these things to discourage you.<lb/> It
                is one comfort that though error may<lb/> triumph for an age or century, time
                will<lb/> eventually give <hi rend="underline">truth</hi> the unfading victory.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Excuse me for this interruption<lb/> of your studies by a few
                friendly words,<lb/> and believe me</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Yours most respectfully,</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)"><persName role="author">M. R. Miller</persName>.</p>
        </body>
